_:genid196 <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#List> .
_:genid192 <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#onProperty> <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0000052> .
_:genid192 <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Restriction> .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000005> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "A property is a material trait in terms of the kind and magnitude of response to a specific imposed stimulus. Generally, definitions of properties are made independent of material shape and size.\n(Callister, W.D., Rethwisch, D.G., Materials Science and Engineering, Wiley, 2014)\n\nTechnical materials are complex aggregates. Many properties that are determined for those aggregates are intrinsically associated with the methodologies employed in the measurement process. This is in contrast to typical 'physical' properties, which like e.g. mass that can be determined to high accuracy independently of the measurement process. \nAs a consequence, material properties in the ontology are differeciated according to their measurement method, e.g. Brinell hardness and Vickers hardness are different types of indentation hardness rather than different measures/quantification (GDC) of the materials property 'indentation hardness'.\n The 'unit idenifieres' of such properties (e.g. \"HV1\", \"HV10\", \"HBW\") are strictly speaking not units but rather references to the measurement methodology used to determine a numeric value that quantifies the property.\n\nExtensive properties that depend on the object being tested rather than on the portion of matter are (extensive) object- or system-properties."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000005> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "material property"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000005> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "a disposition of a portion of matter that is realized in a compatible process and whose realization is grounded in the portions intensive qualities"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000005> <https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000060> "true"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#boolean> .
_:genid197 <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Axiom> .
_:genid197 <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#annotatedSource> <https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000005> .
_:genid197 <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#annotatedProperty> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> .
_:genid197 <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#annotatedTarget> _:genid192 .
_:genid197 <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Due to the duality of object and portion of matter this axiom can not be an equivalent class axiom."@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000007
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000007> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000007> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0001933> .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000007> <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000116> "also see \"The Ontology of Fields\" - Report of a specialist meeting held under the auspices of the varenius project: Donna Peuquet, Barry Smith, and Berit Brogaard; Bar Harbor, Maine 1998"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000007> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "vector field specification"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000007> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Vector field specification is a value specification that represents an assignment of a vector to each point in a discretized spatial region."@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000008
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000008> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000008> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000003> .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000008> <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000116> "an attribute of a process" .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000008> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Process attribute for a process has a similar application to specifically dependened continuant (SDC) for an independent continuant (IC). Furthermore, process attribute describes how SDCs of some participants, i.e., ICs, change in a process. \n\nSpecific rates, e.g., tensile rate, cooling rate, etc. should be added as  subclasses of this class."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000008> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "process attribute"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000008> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#seeAlso> "process attribute from OEO https://openenergyplatform.org/ontology/oeo/OEO_00030019"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000008> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#versionInfo> "Renamed to avoid confusion with has characteristic object property"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000008> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#altLabel> "process characteristic"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000008> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "a process attribute is a dependent occurrent that existentially depends on a process."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000008> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "Tensile rate in a tensile testing process. Cooling rate in a quenching process"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000008> <https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000060> "true"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#boolean> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000010
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000010> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000010> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000591> .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000010> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "workflow function"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000010> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "A plan specification representing a callable software method that prescribes a specific computational action, including execution instructions and a defined set of input and output specifications."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000010> <https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0001032> "https://github.com/materialdigital/core-ontology/issues/246" .
