<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020167> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "structural boundary"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020167> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Structural phase boundary is a phase boundary that is realized in the transition from one structure to another structure."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020167> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "ɑ-Ɣ transformation in iron at 910 °C"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020168
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020168> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020168> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000882> .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020168> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "magnetic boundary"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020168> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "A magnetic boundary is a phase boundary that is realized by the transition from one magnetic ordering to another magnetic ordering."@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020169
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020169> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020169> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0000882> .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020169> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "mixture boundary"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020169> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "A mixture boundary is a phase boundary that is realized by the transition from one phase to another phase in a system involving also chemical variations."@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020170
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020170> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020170> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000030> .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020170> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "The ingot may be hot rolled after casting..."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020170> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Bramme"@de .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020170> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "ingot"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020170> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "An ingot is an object that has a thick section and may bear a semi finished product role and that is the specified output of a casting process. At the same time it is a material."@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020171
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020171> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020171> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000146> .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020171> <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000116> "Should it have exactly two phases as member parts?"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020171> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "phase boundary (spatial)"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020171> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "A fiat surface separating one phase from another phase."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pmd/co/PMD_0020171> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "The phase boundary between liquid and the gaseous phase in a tank. \nThe phase boundary between Fe3C and Fe of a pearlite lamellae."@en .
